    <!-- 01 -->
    <div id="s1" class="section active">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">01</span>
        <span class="section-title">Introduction</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">🧠</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Why Learn Assembly?</h3>
      <p>Assembly is the <strong>closest representation of how a CPU actually executes code</strong>. High-level languages (C, Python) hide this complexity — but attackers can't rely on abstraction.</p>
      <div class="callout">
        <div class="label">Key Idea</div>
        Assembly is not about syntax — it's about understanding execution.
      </div>
      <h3>In Red Team Context</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Reverse engineering binaries</li>
        <li>Writing exploits</li>
        <li>Understanding memory corruption</li>
        <li>Bypassing protections (ASLR, NX, stack canaries...)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 02 -->
    <div id="s2" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">02</span>
        <span class="section-title">Refresher</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Number Bases</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>base</th><th>name</th><th>example</th></tr>
        <tr><td>2</td><td>Binary</td><td>0b11111111</td></tr>
        <tr><td>16</td><td>Hex</td><td>0xFF = 255</td></tr>
        <tr><td>10</td><td>Decimal</td><td>255</td></tr>
      </table>
      <div class="callout orange">
        <div class="label">Why Hex?</div>
        Memory addresses, opcodes, and payloads are almost always expressed in hex. Get very comfortable with it.
      </div>
      <h3>Two's Complement</h3>
      <p>Used to represent <strong>negative numbers</strong> in binary. The CPU doesn't know "negative" — it just sees bit patterns.</p>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="cmt">; -1 in 32-bit two's complement</span>
-1 → <span class="num">0xFFFFFFFF</span>
<span class="cmt">; -1 in 64-bit</span>
-1 → <span class="num">0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF</span>
      </div>
      <h3>C Data Type Sizes (x64)</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>type</th><th>size</th></tr>
        <tr><td>char</td><td>1 byte</td></tr>
        <tr><td>int</td><td>4 bytes</td></tr>
        <tr><td>long</td><td>8 bytes</td></tr>
        <tr><td>pointer</td><td>8 bytes</td></tr>
      </table>
      <h3>Endianness</h3>
      <p>x86-64 uses <strong>Little Endian</strong>: least significant byte stored first.</p>
      <div class="code-block">
Value: <span class="num">0x12345678</span>
In memory: <span class="num">78 56 34 12</span>
      </div>
      <div class="callout red">
        <div class="label">Red Team Impact</div>
        Exploit payloads must account for endianness when writing addresses into memory. A wrong byte order = crash, not shell.
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 03 -->
    <div id="s3" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">03</span>
        <span class="section-title">Registers</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">💾</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Memory Hierarchy</h3>
      <div class="memory-ladder">
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">fastest</div><div class="mem-val hi">Registers (bytes)</div></div>
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">↓</div><div class="mem-val">Cache (MB)</div></div>
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">↓</div><div class="mem-val">RAM (GB)</div></div>
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">slowest</div><div class="mem-val">Disk (TB)</div></div>
      </div>
      <h3>General Purpose Registers</h3>
      <div class="grid2">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-title">64-bit registers</div>
          <div class="reg-row"><span class="reg-name">rax</span><span class="reg-desc">return value / accumulator</span></div>
          <div class="reg-row"><span class="reg-name">rbx</span><span class="reg-desc">base (callee-saved)</span></div>
          <div class="reg-row"><span class="reg-name">rcx</span><span class="reg-desc">counter / 4th arg</span></div>
          <div class="reg-row"><span class="reg-name">rdx</span><span class="reg-desc">data / 3rd arg</span></div>
          <div class="reg-row"><span class="reg-name">rsi</span><span class="reg-desc">source / 2nd arg</span></div>
          <div class="reg-row"><span class="reg-name">rdi</span><span class="reg-desc">destination / 1st arg</span></div>
          <div class="reg-row"><span class="reg-name">r8 – r15</span><span class="reg-desc">general purpose</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-title">special registers</div>
          <div class="reg-row"><span class="reg-name">rsp</span><span class="reg-desc">stack pointer</span></div>
          <div class="reg-row"><span class="reg-name">rbp</span><span class="reg-desc">base / frame pointer</span></div>
          <div class="reg-row"><span class="reg-name">rip</span><span class="reg-desc">instruction pointer</span></div>
          <div class="reg-row"><span class="reg-name">rflags</span><span class="reg-desc">flags (ZF, SF, CF, OF...)</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <h3>Register Size Aliases (example: rax)</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>name</th><th>bits</th><th>bytes</th></tr>
        <tr><td>rax</td><td>64</td><td>8</td></tr>
        <tr><td>eax</td><td>32</td><td>4</td></tr>
        <tr><td>ax</td><td>16</td><td>2</td></tr>
        <tr><td>ah</td><td>8 (high)</td><td>1</td></tr>
        <tr><td>al</td><td>8 (low)</td><td>1</td></tr>
      </table>
      <div class="callout orange">
        <div class="label">Important</div>
        Writing to <strong>eax</strong> zero-extends into rax (clears upper 32 bits). Writing to ax/ah/al does NOT clear the rest.
      </div>
      <h3>Flags Register (rflags)</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>flag</th><th>meaning</th><th>set when</th></tr>
        <tr><td>ZF</td><td>Zero Flag</td><td>result == 0</td></tr>
        <tr><td>SF</td><td>Sign Flag</td><td>result is negative</td></tr>
        <tr><td>CF</td><td>Carry Flag</td><td>unsigned overflow</td></tr>
        <tr><td>OF</td><td>Overflow Flag</td><td>signed overflow</td></tr>
        <tr><td>PF</td><td>Parity Flag</td><td>low byte has even parity</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 04 -->
    <div id="s4" class="section">
