        <span class="section-emoji">🧬</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">nop</span>   <span class="cmt">; no operation — does nothing, advances RIP by 1</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Uses</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Alignment:</strong> pad code to memory boundaries</li>
        <li><strong>Debugging:</strong> placeholder for patching</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="redteam-box">
        <div class="rt-label">Red Team — NOP Sled</div>
        <ul>
          <li>A sequence of NOPs before shellcode</li>
          <li>Increases the landing zone for imprecise jumps</li>
          <li><code style="color:#ef9a9a;font-family:var(--mono)">\x90\x90\x90\x90...[shellcode]</code></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 05 -->
    <div id="s5" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">05</span>
        <span class="section-title">The Stack</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">📦</span>
      </div>
      <p>The stack is a <strong>LIFO</strong> (Last In, First Out) structure used for function calls, local variables, and return addresses.</p>
      <h3>Key Instructions</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">push</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>   <span class="cmt">; RSP -= 8, then [RSP] = rax</span>
<span class="kw">pop</span>  <span class="reg">rax</span>   <span class="cmt">; rax = [RSP], then RSP += 8</span>
      </div>
      <div class="callout red">
        <div class="label">Critical</div>
        The stack grows <strong>downward</strong>. Higher addresses = older data. RSP always points to the top (lowest address).
      </div>
      <h3>Stack Layout Visualization</h3>
      <div class="memory-ladder">
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">0x7fff...high</div><div class="mem-val">older stack frames</div></div>
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">[RBP+16]</div><div class="mem-val">function arguments (extra)</div></div>
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">[RBP+8]</div><div class="mem-val">return address</div></div>
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">[RBP]</div><div class="mem-val">saved old RBP</div></div>
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">[RBP-8]</div><div class="mem-val">local variable 1</div></div>
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">[RBP-16]</div><div class="mem-val">local variable 2</div></div>
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">← RSP</div><div class="mem-val sp">top of stack (lowest addr)</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 06 -->
    <div id="s6" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">06</span>
        <span class="section-title">Calling Functions</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">📞</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">call</span> <span class="lbl">func</span>   <span class="cmt">; push RIP (return addr), jmp to func</span>
<span class="lbl">func:</span>
    <span class="kw">push</span> <span class="reg">rbp</span>
    <span class="kw">mov</span>  <span class="reg">rbp</span>, <span class="reg">rsp</span>
    <span class="cmt">; ... function body ...</span>
    <span class="kw">pop</span>  <span class="reg">rbp</span>
    <span class="kw">ret</span>        <span class="cmt">; pop return addr, jmp back</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Basic Arithmetic Instructions</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>instruction</th><th>syntax</th><th>effect</th></tr>
        <tr><td>mov</td><td>mov dst, src</td><td>dst = src</td></tr>
        <tr><td>add</td><td>add dst, src</td><td>dst = dst + src</td></tr>
        <tr><td>sub</td><td>sub dst, src</td><td>dst = dst - src</td></tr>
      </table>
      <div class="callout">
        <div class="label">Intel Syntax Rule</div>
        Destination is always <strong>left</strong>: <code style="font-family:var(--mono)">mov rax, rbx</code> means rax ← rbx.
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 07 -->
    <div id="s7" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">07</span>
        <span class="section-title">Local Variables</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">🧱</span>
      </div>
      <p>Local variables live on the stack below RBP.</p>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="cmt">; Standard function prologue</span>
<span class="kw">push</span> <span class="reg">rbp</span>
<span class="kw">mov</span>  <span class="reg">rbp</span>, <span class="reg">rsp</span>
<span class="kw">sub</span>  <span class="reg">rsp</span>, <span class="num">32</span>     <span class="cmt">; reserve 32 bytes for locals</span>
 
<span class="cmt">; Access local vars</span>
<span class="kw">mov</span> [<span class="reg">rbp</span>-<span class="num">8</span>], <span class="reg">rax</span>  <span class="cmt">; store into local var</span>
<span class="kw">mov</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, [<span class="reg">rbp</span>-<span class="num">8</span>]  <span class="cmt">; load from local var</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Arrays</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="cmt">; arr[i] = base + i * element_size</span>
<span class="kw">mov</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, [<span class="reg">rbx</span> + <span class="reg">rcx</span>*<span class="num">8</span>]   <span class="cmt">; 64-bit array access</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Structs</h3>
      <p>Fields stored sequentially in memory. Compiler may add <strong>padding</strong> for alignment (fields aligned to their size).</p>
      <h3>New Instructions</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>instruction</th><th>syntax</th><th>use</th></tr>
        <tr><td>imul</td><td>imul rax, rbx</td><td>signed multiply</td></tr>
        <tr><td>movsx</td><td>movsx rax, eax</td><td>sign-extend (preserves sign)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>movzx</td><td>movzx rax, al</td><td>zero-extend (fills with 0s)</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 08 -->
    <div id="s8" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">08</span>
        <span class="section-title">Function Parameters</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">📥</span>
      </div>
      <h3>x64 Linux Calling Convention (System V ABI)</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>arg #</th><th>register</th></tr>
        <tr><td>1st</td><td>rdi</td></tr>
        <tr><td>2nd</td><td>rsi</td></tr>
        <tr><td>3rd</td><td>rdx</td></tr>
        <tr><td>4th</td><td>rcx</td></tr>
        <tr><td>5th</td><td>r8</td></tr>
        <tr><td>6th</td><td>r9</td></tr>
        <tr><td>7th+</td><td>pushed on stack (right to left)</td></tr>
      </table>
      <h3>Return Value</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="reg">rax</span>  <span class="cmt">; primary return value</span>
<span class="reg">rdx</span>  <span class="cmt">; secondary (e.g., 128-bit results)</span>
      </div>
      <div class="callout orange">
        <div class="label">Callee-saved vs Caller-saved</div>
        <strong>Callee-saved (must preserve):</strong> rbx, rbp, r12–r15<br>
        <strong>Caller-saved (may clobber):</strong> rax, rcx, rdx, rsi, rdi, r8–r11
      </div>
      <h3>32-bit Difference</h3>
      <p>In 32-bit x86, <strong>all parameters are passed on the stack</strong>. No register-based argument passing.</p>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 09 -->
    <div id="s9" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">09</span>
        <span class="section-title">LEA — Load Effective Address</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">🧠</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">lea</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, [<span class="reg">rbx</span> + <span class="reg">rcx</span>*<span class="num">4</span> + <span class="num">8</span>]
<span class="cmt">; rax = rbx + rcx*4 + 8</span>
<span class="cmt">; does NOT dereference memory — pure arithmetic!</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Why Use LEA?</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fast multiplication</strong> by 2, 4, 8 without mul instruction</li>
        <li><strong>Pointer arithmetic</strong> — compute an address without loading the value</li>
        <li>Single instruction does add + shift</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="cmt">; Example: rax = rbx * 5</span>
<span class="kw">lea</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, [<span class="reg">rbx</span> + <span class="reg">rbx</span>*<span class="num">4</span>]
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 10 -->
    <div id="s10" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">10</span>
        <span class="section-title">Control Flow</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">🔁</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Unconditional Jump</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">jmp</span> <span class="lbl">label</span>   <span class="cmt">; always jump</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Conditional Jumps (after cmp)</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">cmp</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, <span class="reg">rbx</span>   <span class="cmt">; computes rax - rbx, sets flags</span>
<span class="kw">je</span>  <span class="lbl">label</span>     <span class="cmt">; jump if equal (ZF=1)</span>
<span class="kw">jne</span> <span class="lbl">label</span>     <span class="cmt">; jump if not equal (ZF=0)</span>
<span class="kw">jg</span>  <span class="lbl">label</span>     <span class="cmt">; jump if greater (signed)</span>
<span class="kw">jl</span>  <span class="lbl">label</span>     <span class="cmt">; jump if less (signed)</span>
<span class="kw">ja</span>  <span class="lbl">label</span>     <span class="cmt">; jump if above (unsigned)</span>
<span class="kw">jb</span>  <span class="lbl">label</span>     <span class="cmt">; jump if below (unsigned)</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Switch Statements</h3>
      <p>Compilers implement <code style="font-family:var(--mono);color:var(--accent)">switch</code> as <strong>jump tables</strong> — an array of code pointers, indexed by the switch value. Very common in reverse engineering.</p>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="cmt">; Pseudo-implementation of switch(rax)</span>
<span class="kw">cmp</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, <span class="num">3</span>
<span class="kw">ja</span>  <span class="lbl">default_case</span>
<span class="kw">jmp</span> [<span class="reg">jump_table</span> + <span class="reg">rax</span>*<span class="num">8</span>]
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 11 -->
    <div id="s11" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">11</span>
        <span class="section-title">Boolean Logic</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">🧠</span>
      </div>
      <table>
        <tr><th>instruction</th><th>effect</th><th>common use</th></tr>
        <tr><td>and</td><td>bitwise AND</td><td>masking bits</td></tr>
        <tr><td>or</td><td>bitwise OR</td><td>setting bits</td></tr>
        <tr><td>xor</td><td>bitwise XOR</td><td>toggling, zeroing regs</td></tr>
        <tr><td>not</td><td>bitwise NOT</td><td>invert all bits</td></tr>
      </table>
      <h3>Common Idioms</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">xor</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, <span class="reg">rax</span>     <span class="cmt">; zero rax (fastest way)</span>
<span class="kw">and</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, <span class="num">0xFF</span>   <span class="cmt">; keep only low byte</span>
<span class="kw">or</span>  <span class="reg">rax</span>, <span class="num">1</span>      <span class="cmt">; set bit 0</span>
      </div>
      <h3>TEST Instruction</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">test</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, <span class="reg">rax</span>   <span class="cmt">; like AND but discards result</span>
<span class="kw">jz</span>   <span class="lbl">is_zero</span>   <span class="cmt">; if rax == 0, jump</span>
<span class="cmt">; equivalent to: if (rax == 0) ...</span>
      </div>
      <div class="callout">
        <div class="label">Why test instead of cmp?</div>
        <code style="font-family:var(--mono)">test rax, rax</code> is 1 byte shorter than <code style="font-family:var(--mono)">cmp rax, 0</code>. Compilers prefer it.
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 12 -->
    <div id="s12" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">12</span>
        <span class="section-title">Loops</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">🔄</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Classic Loop Pattern</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">mov</span>  <span class="reg">rcx</span>, <span class="num">10</span>      <span class="cmt">; counter = 10</span>
<span class="lbl">loop_start:</span>
    <span class="cmt">; ... loop body ...</span>
    <span class="kw">dec</span>  <span class="reg">rcx</span>         <span class="cmt">; rcx -= 1</span>
    <span class="kw">jnz</span>  <span class="lbl">loop_start</span>  <span class="cmt">; jump if rcx != 0</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Inc / Dec</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">inc</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>   <span class="cmt">; rax += 1 (doesn't set CF)</span>
<span class="kw">dec</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>   <span class="cmt">; rax -= 1 (doesn't set CF)</span>
      </div>
      <div class="callout orange">
        <div class="label">Note</div>
        inc/dec set ZF and SF but <strong>do NOT set CF</strong>. Use add/sub if you need carry flag.
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 13 -->
    <div id="s13" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">13</span>
        <span class="section-title">Bit Shifting</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">🔀</span>
      </div>
      <table>
        <tr><th>instruction</th><th>direction</th><th>fill</th><th>used for</th></tr>
        <tr><td>shl</td><td>left</td><td>0s from right</td><td>multiply by 2^n</td></tr>
        <tr><td>shr</td><td>right</td><td>0s from left</td><td>unsigned divide by 2^n</td></tr>
        <tr><td>sar</td><td>right</td><td>sign bit</td><td>signed divide by 2^n</td></tr>
      </table>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">shl</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, <span class="num">3</span>   <span class="cmt">; rax *= 8  (2^3)</span>
<span class="kw">shr</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, <span class="num">1</span>   <span class="cmt">; rax /= 2  (unsigned)</span>
<span class="kw">sar</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, <span class="num">1</span>   <span class="cmt">; rax /= 2  (signed, preserves sign)</span>
      </div>
      <h3>CDQ</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">cdq</span>   <span class="cmt">; sign-extend EAX into EDX:EAX</span>
<span class="cmt">; required before idiv in 32-bit mode</span>
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 14 -->
    <div id="s14" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">14</span>
        <span class="section-title">Multiply &amp; Divide</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">✖️➗</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Multiply</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">mul</span>  <span class="reg">rbx</span>        <span class="cmt">; unsigned: rdx:rax = rax * rbx</span>
<span class="kw">imul</span> <span class="reg">rbx</span>        <span class="cmt">; signed:   rdx:rax = rax * rbx</span>
<span class="kw">imul</span> <span class="reg">rax</span>, <span class="reg">rbx</span>  <span class="cmt">; 2-op form: rax = rax * rbx</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Divide</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="cmt">; Setup before div:</span>
<span class="kw">xor</span> <span class="reg">rdx</span>, <span class="reg">rdx</span>   <span class="cmt">; clear rdx (unsigned)</span>
<span class="kw">div</span> <span class="reg">rbx</span>        <span class="cmt">; rax = rdx:rax / rbx</span>
                 <span class="cmt">; rdx = rdx:rax % rbx</span>
      </div>
      <div class="callout red">
        <div class="label">Trap</div>
        Dividing by zero causes a <strong>#DE exception</strong> — instant crash. Always validate the divisor before dividing.
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 15 -->
    <div id="s15" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">15</span>
        <span class="section-title">REP Instructions</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">⚡</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">rep stosq</span>   <span class="cmt">; fill memory: [rdi] = rax, rcx times</span>
             <span class="cmt">; → implements memset</span>
 
<span class="kw">rep movsq</span>   <span class="cmt">; copy memory: [rdi] ← [rsi], rcx times</span>
             <span class="cmt">; → implements memcpy</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Register Roles</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>register</th><th>role in REP</th></tr>
        <tr><td>rcx</td><td>count (decremented each iteration)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>rdi</td><td>destination pointer</td></tr>
        <tr><td>rsi</td><td>source pointer (movsq only)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>rax</td><td>fill value (stosq only)</td></tr>
      </table>
      <div class="callout green">
        <div class="label">Why It Matters</div>
        You'll see rep stos/movs constantly in compiled C code wherever memset/memcpy is used. Recognizing this pattern speeds up reverse engineering significantly.
      </div>
    </div>
 
