    <!-- 17 -->
    <div id="s17" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">17</span>
        <span class="section-title">Binary Bomb Lab</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">💣</span>
      </div>
      <p>A classic CTF-style exercise: a binary with multiple "phases", each requiring the right input to defuse. Wrong input = "BOOM".</p>
      <h3>Goal</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Reverse engineer each phase's logic</li>
        <li>Understand what input satisfies the checks</li>
        <li>Never actually run the bomb with wrong input</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Tools Used</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>tool</th><th>purpose</th></tr>
        <tr><td>GDB</td><td>dynamic analysis — run and step</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Ghidra</td><td>static analysis — decompile to C-like code</td></tr>
        <tr><td>IDA Pro</td><td>professional-grade disassembler / decompiler</td></tr>
      </table>
      <div class="callout green">
        <div class="label">Approach</div>
        Set a breakpoint before each comparison. Inspect registers to see what value is expected. Work backwards from the check.
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- 18 -->
    <div id="s18" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-num">18</span>
        <span class="section-title">Buffer Overflow</span>
        <span class="section-emoji">💥</span>
      </div>
      <div class="callout red">
        <div class="label">Optional but Critical for Red Team</div>
        Buffer overflow is the foundation of most memory corruption exploits.
      </div>
      <h3>The Idea</h3>
      <p>A buffer on the stack has a fixed size. If user input exceeds that size and there's no bounds check, it overwrites adjacent memory — including the <strong>return address</strong>.</p>
      <div class="memory-ladder">
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">[RBP+8]</div><div class="mem-val">return address ← target</div></div>
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">[RBP]</div><div class="mem-val">saved RBP</div></div>
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">[RBP-8]</div><div class="mem-val">local buffer[64]</div></div>
        <div class="mem-row"><div class="mem-addr">overflow →</div><div class="mem-val sp">input fills past buffer end</div></div>
      </div>
      <h3>Classic Exploit Flow</h3>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="num">1.</span> Find the offset to return address
<span class="num">2.</span> Craft input: [padding][target address]
<span class="num">3.</span> Control RIP → redirect execution
<span class="num">4.</span> Jump to shellcode or gadget chain (ROP)
      </div>
      <h3>Modern Protections</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>protection</th><th>what it does</th><th>bypass technique</th></tr>
        <tr><td>ASLR</td><td>randomize memory layout</td><td>info leak, brute force</td></tr>
        <tr><td>NX / DEP</td><td>non-executable stack</td><td>ROP chains</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Stack canary</td><td>detect stack corruption</td><td>leak the canary</td></tr>
        <tr><td>PIE</td><td>randomize code address</td><td>info leak</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
 
